The accident occurred on August 22, 2012, at 11:40 Local time.
The accident occurred in Hernando Beach, Florida.
The aircraft involved was a Piper PA-28RT-201T.
The aircraft registration was N2970G.
The defining event was loss of engine power (partial).
The flight was conducted under Part 91: General aviation - Personal.
The accident number was ERA12LA522.
The aircraft sustained substantial damage.
There were no injuries to the sole occupant.
The pilot was flying over the Gulf of Mexico when the incident occurred.
The engine began to run rough during the flight.
The engine experienced a partial loss of power during the flight.
The pilot declared an emergency after experiencing engine problems.
The pilot searched for a place to land after the engine problems began.
The pilot performed a gear-up landing in the water.
The pilot egressed from the aircraft after landing.
The pilot was rescued by the U.S. Coast Guard.
A postaccident engine examination was conducted.
The examination revealed the No. 6 cylinder fuel injection nozzle was blocked with debris.
The fuel nozzle was cleaned after the examination.
The fuel nozzle was reinstalled after being cleaned.
An engine run was performed after the fuel nozzle was cleaned and reinstalled.
The engine started and ran smoothly during the test run.
The engine accelerated to maximum power without hesitation during the test run.
The engine was shut down with no anomalies noted during the test run.
A small particle of debris in the fuel likely became lodged in the No. 6 fuel injection nozzle.
The debris in the fuel injection nozzle resulted in the loss of engine power.
The National Transportation Safety Board determined the probable cause of the accident.
The probable cause was a partial loss of engine power due to a blockage of the No. 6 cylinder fuel injector nozzle.
The finding identified the fuel injector nozzle malfunction as the cause.

text:
# Aviation Investigation Final Report

## Location:
Hernando Beach, Florida

## Date & Time: 
August 22, 2012, 11:40 Local

## Aircraft:
Piper PA-28RT-201T

## Defining Event:
Loss of engine power (partial)

## Flight Conducted Under:
Part 91: General aviation - Personal

## Accident Number:
ERA12LA522

## Registration:
N2970G

## Aircraft Damage:
Substantial

## Injuries:
1 None

## Analysis
While en route over the Gulf of Mexico, the pilot reported that the engine began to run rough and experienced a partial loss of power. The pilot declared an emergency, searched for a place to land, and performed a gear-up landing in the water. The pilot egressed and was rescued by the U.S. Coast Guard. A postaccident engine examination revealed that the No.6 cylinder fuel injection nozzle was blocked with debris. After the fuel nozzle was cleaned and reinstalled, an engine run was performed. The engine started and ran smoothly, accelerated to maximum power without hesitation, and was shut down with no anomalies noted. It is likely that a small particle of debris in the fuel became lodged in the No. 6 fuel injection nozzle, which resulted in the loss of engine power.

## Probable Cause and Findings
The National Transportation Safety Board determines the probable cause(s) of this accident to be:
A partial loss of engine power due to a blockage of the No. 6 cylinder fuel injector nozzle.

## Findings
| Aircraft | Fuel injector nozzle - Malfunction |
